  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in the streets of Naples, in the quiet moments when my kids ask why their teacher says girls aren't good at math. It's the fear that when you're a young person from a working-class background, especially if you're gay or your family didn't go far in education, you might not be 'smart enough' for a field that seems to demand a lot more than what you've been taught. For me, as a cleaner with a vocational diploma, I know that STEM isn't always about the textbooks or the lab coats—it's about real-world problem-solving. But the idea that someone from my background can't handle the pressure of a math test or a science project? That's a real threat. I think we should address it, but not with big, top-down policies that ignore the everyday struggles of people like me. Instead, we need to create spaces where students feel safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. Maybe start in schools by having teachers who understand the social dynamics and the anxiety that comes with being the 'first' or the 'only' in a room. It's not about changing the system overnight, but about making sure that everyone has the chance to believe in themselves, even if they don't have the same advantages as others.",
